07642nam a22015375i 9780691240947DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912409477 a10.1515/97806912409472doi  a(DE-B1597)635213  a(OCoLC)1347247577  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS145b.D675 2023 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a305.89242231 aDorin, Rowan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Return :bJews, Christian Usurers, and the Spread of Mass Expulsion in Medieval Europe /cRowan Dorin. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b5 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistories of Economic Life ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA note on usage -- tIntroduction -- tPART I -- t1 Expulsion, Jews, and Usury: trajectories of christian thought and practice -- t2 Inventing Expulsion in England, 1154–1272 -- t3 Inventing Expulsion in France, 1144–1270 -- tPART II -- t4 Canonizing Expulsion: the second council of Lyon, 1274 -- t5 Disseminating Expulsion: synods, summas, and sermons -- tPART III -- t6 Emulating Expulsion: England and France, 1274–1306 -- t7 Ignoring Expulsion: episcopal evasion and papal inaction, 1274–1400 -- t8 Expanding (and Impeding) Expulsion: Jews, usury, and canon law, 1300–1492 -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix A: Timeline of Expulsions of Jews and Christian Usurers, 1100–ca. 135 -- tAppendix B: Usury and Expulsion in Local Ecclesiastical Legislation, 1200-ca. 1400 -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tList of manuscripts and archival series consulted -- tIndex -- tA NOTE ON THE TYPE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking new history of the shared legacy of expulsion among Jews and Christian moneylenders in late medieval EuropeBeginning in the twelfth century, Jewish moneylenders increasingly found themselves in the crosshairs of European authorities, who denounced the evils of usury as they expelled Jews from their lands. Yet Jews were not alone in supplying coin and credit to needy borrowers. Across much of Western Europe, foreign Christians likewise engaged in professional moneylending, and they too faced repeated threats of expulsion from the communities in which they settled. No Return examines how mass expulsion became a pervasive feature of European law and politics—with tragic consequences that have reverberated down to the present.Drawing on unpublished archival evidence ranging from fiscal ledgers and legal opinions to sermons and student notebooks, Rowan Dorin traces how an association between usury and expulsion entrenched itself in Latin Christendom from the twelfth century onward. Showing how ideas and practices of expulsion were imitated and repurposed in different contexts, he offers a provocative reconsideration of the dynamics of persecution in late medieval society.Uncovering the protean and contagious nature of expulsion, No Return is a panoramic work of history that offers new perspectives on Jewish-Christian relations, the circulation of norms and ideas in the age before print, and the intersection of law, religion, and economic life in premodern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExile (Punishment)zEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aExile (Punishment). 0aJewsxPersecutionszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewsxPersecutionszEurope. 0aMoneylenderszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPersecutionzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUsury lawszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUsuryxReligious aspects. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAaron of Lincoln.  aAbbess.  aAbeyance.  aAccrual.  aAdvocatus.  aAttempt.  aAuvergne.  aAuxerre.  aBis